  "summary": "Roger and Frankie discuss the influence of Dr. Nicholson and the necessity of preventing Henry Bashington-French from going to Grange. During their conversation in the garden, they hear a gunshot coming from inside the house. They rush to the hallway, where they find a pale Sylvia Baskin-French. Finding the study door locked, Roger breaks the study window to gain entry. Inside, they discover Henry sprawled across his desk with a gunshot wound to his temple and a revolver on the floor.\n\nDr. Nicholson arrives shortly after the discovery. He examines the body and declares Henry dead, noting a piece of paper near Henry's elbow. The note, written by Henry, expresses his inability to fight a \"deadly habit\" and offers blessings to Sylvia and Tommy. Frankie finds the study key in Henry's outer coat pocket, which allows her to unlock the door from the hallway.\n\nThe following morning, Frankie meets with Bobby to discuss the event. While Frankie maintains that Henry committed suicide—noting that the door was locked and the window was shut—Bobby expresses suspicion. He suggests that Dr. Nicholson may have murdered Henry, forced him to write a suicide note, and then staged his arrival. Bobby points out that Nicholson was the one who \"found\" the key in Henry's pocket, suggesting the discovery could have been faked. Frankie counters that she was watching Nicholson closely and insists the key was definitely in the pocket.",
